1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,872
Book XII.

2
00:00:01,193 --> 00:00:04,497
The Sirens, Scylla, and Charybdis, the Cattle of the Sun.

3
00:00:05,378 --> 00:00:14,130
After we were clear of the river Oceanus and had got out into the open sea, we went on till we reached the Aean island where there is dawn and sunrise as in other places.

4
00:00:14,811 --> 00:00:20,699
We then drew our ship onto the sands and got out of her onto the shore where we went to sleep and waited till day should break.

5
00:00:21,220 --> 00:00:28,570
Then, when the child of morning, rosy-fingered Dawn, appeared, I sent some men to Circe's house to fetch the body of Elpenor.

6
00:00:28,837 --> 00:00:36,529
We cut firewood from a wood where the headland jutted out into the sea, and after we had wept over him and lamented him, we performed his funeral rites.

7
00:00:37,070 --> 00:00:46,204
When his body and armor had been burned to ashes, we raised a cairn, set a stone over it, and at the top of the cairn we fixed the oar that he had been used to row with.

8
00:00:46,184 --> 00:00:57,398
While we were doing all this, Circe, who knew that we had got back from the house of Hades, dressed herself and came to us as fast as she could, and her maidservants came with her bringing us bread, meat, and wine.

9
00:00:57,899 --> 00:01:06,610
Then she stood in the midst of us and said, You have done a bold thing in going down alive to the house of Hades, and you will have died twice, to other peoples once.

10
00:01:07,051 --> 00:01:13,339
Now then, stay here for the rest of the day, feast your fill, and go on with your voyage at daybreak tomorrow morning.

11
00:01:13,319 --> 00:01:21,935
In the meantime, I will tell Ulysses about your course and will explain everything to him so as to prevent your suffering from misadventure either by land or sea."

12
00:01:22,537 --> 00:01:33,758
We agreed to do as she had said and feasted through the livelong day to the going down of the sun, but when the sun had set and it came on dark, the men laid themselves down to sleep by the stern cables of the ship.

13
00:01:33,738 --> 00:01:41,169
Then Circe took me by the hand and bade me be seated away from the others, while she reclined by my side and asked me all about our adventures.

14
00:01:41,690 --> 00:01:47,339
So far so good, said she, when I had ended my story, and now pay attention to what I am about to tell you.

15
00:01:47,659 --> 00:01:50,764
Heaven itself, indeed, will recall it to your recollection.

16
00:01:51,204 --> 00:01:54,309
First you will come to the sirens, who enchant all who come near them.

17
00:01:54,950 --> 00:01:59,577
If anyone unwarily draws in too close and hears the singing of the sirens,

18
00:01:59,557 --> 00:02:07,778
His wife and children will never welcome him home again, for they sit in a green field and warble him to death with the sweetness of their song.

19
00:02:07,893 --> 00:02:13,179
There is a great heap of dead men's bones lying all around, with the flesh still rotting off them.

20
00:02:13,900 --> 00:02:18,826
Therefore pass these sirens by, and stop your men's ears with wax that none of them may hear.

21
00:02:19,507 --> 00:02:31,622
But if you like you can listen yourself, for you may get the men to bind you as you stand upright on a cross-piece halfway up the mast, ninety-nine, and they must lash the rope's ends to the mast itself, that you may have the pleasure of listening.

22
00:02:31,602 --> 00:02:35,972
If you beg and pray the men to unloose you, then they must bind you faster.

23
00:02:36,494 --> 00:02:41,365
When your crew have taken you past these sirens, I cannot give you coherent directions.

24
00:02:41,886 --> 00:02:49,324
S-100, as to which of two courses you are to take, I will lay the two alternatives before you, and you must consider them for yourself.

25
00:02:49,304 --> 00:02:56,096
On the one hand, there are some overhanging rocks against which the deep blue waves of Amphitrite beat with terrific fury.

26
00:02:56,597 --> 00:02:59,062
The blessed gods call these rocks the Wanderers.

27
00:02:59,542 --> 00:03:04,972
Here not even a bird may pass, no, not even the timid doves that bring ambrosia to Father Jove.

28
00:03:05,433 --> 00:03:07,978
But the sheer rock always carries off one of them.

29
00:03:08,539 --> 00:03:11,464
And Father Jove has to send another to make up their number.

30
00:03:11,444 --> 00:03:20,260
No ship that ever yet came to these rocks has got away again, but the waves and whirlwinds of fire are freighted with wreckage and with the bodies of dead men.

31
00:03:21,021 --> 00:03:32,862
The only vessel that ever sailed and got through was the famous Argo on her way from the house of Aetis, and she too would have gone against these great rocks, only that Juno piloted her past them for the love she bore to Jason.

32
00:03:32,842 --> 00:03:37,508
Of these two rocks the one reaches heaven, and its peak is lost in a dark cloud.

33
00:03:38,089 --> 00:03:42,896
This never leaves it, so that the top is never clear, not even in summer and early autumn.

34
00:03:43,577 --> 00:03:51,668
No man, though he had twenty hands and twenty feet, could get a foothold on it and climb it, for it runs sheer up, as smooth as though it had been polished.

35
00:03:52,289 --> 00:03:56,514
In the middle of it there is a large cavern, looking west and turned towards Erebus.

36
00:03:56,955 --> 00:03:58,377
You must take your ship this way.

37
00:03:58,357 --> 00:04:02,765
but the cave is so high up that not even the stoutest archer could send an arrow into it.

38
00:04:03,266 --> 00:04:14,307
Inside it, Scylla sits and yelps with a voice that you might take to be that of a young hound, but in truth she is a dreadful monster and no one, not even a god, could face her without being terror-struck.

39
00:04:14,287 --> 00:04:38,539
She has twelve misshapen feet and six necks of the most prodigious length, and at the end of each neck she has a frightful head with three rows of teeth in each, all set very close together so that they would crunch anyone to death in a moment, and she sits deep within her shady cell thrusting out her heads and peering all round the rock, fishing for dolphins or dogfish or any larger monster that she can catch, of the thousands with which Amphitrite teems.

40
00:04:38,519 --> 00:04:45,771
No ship ever yet got past her without losing some men, for she shoots out all her heads at once and carries off a man in each mouth.

41
00:04:46,292 --> 00:04:51,661
You will find the other rock lie lower, but they are so close together that there is not more than a bow shot between them.

42
00:04:52,162 --> 00:04:58,232
A large fig tree in full leafa 101 grows upon it, and under it lies the sucking whirlpool of Charybdis.

43
00:04:58,212 --> 00:05:03,219
Three times in the day does she vomit forth her waters, and three times she sucks them down again.

44
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:08,467
See that you be not there when she is sucking, for if you are Neptune himself could not save you.

45
00:05:08,788 --> 00:05:15,077
You must hug the Scylla side and drive ship by as fast as you can, for you had better lose six men than your whole crew."

46
00:05:15,097 --> 00:05:22,448
"'Is there no way,' said I, of escaping Charybdis, and at the same time keeping Scylla off when she is trying to harm my men?'

47
00:05:22,428 --> 00:05:26,397
You dare devil, reply the goddess, you are always wanting to fight somebody or something.

48
00:05:26,677 --> 00:05:29,263
You will not let yourself be beaten, even by the immortals.

49
00:05:29,924 --> 00:05:31,227
For Scylla is not mortal.

50
00:05:31,448 --> 00:05:35,476
Moreover, she is savage, extreme, rude, cruel and invincible.

51
00:05:35,978 --> 00:05:36,940
There is no help for it.

52
00:05:37,200 --> 00:05:40,808
Your best chance will be to get by her as fast as ever you can.

53
00:05:40,788 --> 00:05:49,040
For if you dawdle about her rock while you are putting on your armor, she may catch you with a second cast of her six heads and snap up another half-dozen of your men.

54
00:05:49,621 --> 00:05:54,949
So drive your ship past her at full speed and roar out lustily to Cratias, who is Scylla's dam.

55
00:05:55,349 --> 00:05:56,130
Bad luck to her.

56
00:05:56,491 --> 00:05:59,235
She will then stop her from making a second raid upon you.

57
00:05:59,772 --> 00:06:06,062
You will now come to the Thrinacian island, and here you will see many herds of cattle and flocks of sheep belonging to the sun god.

58
00:06:06,823 --> 00:06:11,170
Seven herds of cattle and seven flocks of sheep, with fifty head in each flock.

59
00:06:11,190 --> 00:06:20,886
They do not breed, nor do they become fewer in number, and they are tended by the goddesses Feathusa and Lampety, who are children of the sun god Hyperion by Neira.

60
00:06:20,866 --> 00:06:29,516
Their mother, when she had borne them and had done suckling them, sent them to the Thranacian island, which was a long way off, to live there and look after their father's flocks and herds.

61
00:06:30,257 --> 00:06:36,364
If you leave these flocks unharmed and think of nothing but getting home, you may yet after much hardship reach Ithaca.

62
00:06:36,824 --> 00:06:47,717
But if you harm them, then I forewarn you of the destruction both of your ship and of your comrades, and even though you may yourself escape, you will return late in bad plight after losing all your men.

63
00:06:47,697 --> 00:06:53,387
Here she ended, and dawn enthroned in gold began to show in heaven, whereon she returned inland.

64
00:06:53,705 --> 00:07:02,817
I then went on board and told my men to loose the ship from her moorings, so they at once got into her, took their places, and began to smite the grey sea with their oars.

65
00:07:03,678 --> 00:07:16,594
Presently the great and cunning goddess Circe befriended us with a fair wind that blew dead aft, and stayed steadily with us, keeping our sails well filled, so we did whatever wanted doing to the ship's gear, and let her go as wind and helmsman headed her.

66
00:07:17,135 --> 00:07:21,180
Then, being much troubled in mind, I said to my men, my friends,

67
00:07:21,160 --> 00:07:26,025
It is not right that one or two of us alone should know the prophecies that Circe has made me.

68
00:07:26,426 --> 00:07:31,111
I will therefore tell you about them, so that whether we live or die we may do so with our eyes open."

69
00:07:31,752 --> 00:07:41,062
First she said we were to keep clear of the sirens, who sit and sing most beautifully in a field of flowers, but she said I might hear them myself so long as no one else did.

70
00:07:41,803 --> 00:07:50,492
Therefore take me and bind me to the cross-piece halfway up the mast, bind me as I stand upright, with a bond so fast that I cannot possibly break away,

71
00:07:50,472 --> 00:07:53,075
and lash the rope's ends to the mast itself.

72
00:07:53,896 --> 00:07:57,861
If I beg and pray you to set me free, then bind me more tightly still."

73
00:07:58,822 --> 00:08:03,006
I had hardly finished telling everything to the men before we reached the island of the two sirens.

74
00:08:03,427 --> 00:08:06,190
One thousand and two for the wind had been very favorable.

75
00:08:06,691 --> 00:08:08,413
Then all of a sudden it fell dead calm.

76
00:08:08,813 --> 00:08:13,238
There was not a breath of wind nor a ripple upon the water, so the men furled the sails and stowed them.

77
00:08:13,919 --> 00:08:18,184
Then taking to their oars they whitened the water with the foam they raised in rowing.

78
00:08:18,164 --> 00:08:21,974
Meanwhile, I look a large wheel of wax and cut it up small with my sword.

79
00:08:22,756 --> 00:08:30,756
Then I kneaded the wax in my strong hands till it became soft, which it soon did between the kneading and the rays of the sun-god Sun of Hyperion.

80
00:08:31,276 --> 00:08:39,325
Then I stopped the ears of all my men, and they bound me hands and feet to the mast as I stood upright on the crosspiece, but they went on rowing themselves.

81
00:08:39,866 --> 00:08:47,334
When we had got within earshot of the land, and the ship was going at a good rate, the sirens saw that we were getting inshore and began with their singing.

82
00:08:48,015 --> 00:08:54,482
Come here, they sang, renowned Ulysses, honor to the Achaean name, and listen to our two voices.

83
00:08:54,462 --> 00:08:59,310
No one ever sailed past us without staying to hear the enchanting sweetness of our song.

84
00:08:59,911 --> 00:09:12,032
And he who listens will go on his way, not only charmed, but wiser, for we know all the ills that the gods laid upon the Argives and Trojans before Troy, and can tell you everything that is going to happen over the whole world.

85
00:09:13,278 --> 00:09:20,307
They sang these words most musically, and as I longed to hear them further I made signs by frowning to my men that they should set me free.

86
00:09:20,888 --> 00:09:28,478
But they quickened their stroke, and Eurylochus and Perimedes bound me with still stronger bonds till we had got out of hearing of the sirens' voices.

87
00:09:29,139 --> 00:09:32,383
Then my men took the wax from their ears and unbound me.

88
00:09:32,920 --> 00:09:39,573
Immediately after we had got past the island, I saw a great wave from which spray was rising, and I heard a loud roaring sound.

89
00:09:40,275 --> 00:09:49,653
The men were so frightened that they loosed hold of their oars, for the whole sea resounded with the rushing of the waters one hundred and three, but the ship stayed where it was, for the men had left off rowing.

90
00:09:50,194 --> 00:09:54,743
I went round, therefore, and exhorted them man by man not to lose heart.

91
00:09:54,723 --> 00:10:02,730
"'My friends,' said I, "'this is not the first time that we have been in danger, "'and we are in nothing like so bad a case "'as when the Cyclops shut us up in his cave.

92
00:10:02,750 --> 00:10:08,596
"'Nevertheless, my courage and wise counsel saved us then, "'and we shall live to look back on all this as well.

93
00:10:08,616 --> 00:10:14,741
"'Now, therefore, let us all do as I say, "'trust in Jove, and row on with might and main.

94
00:10:14,761 --> 00:10:17,644
"'As for you, Coxson, these are your orders.

95
00:10:17,884 --> 00:10:19,906
"'Attend to them, for the ship is in your hands.

96
00:10:19,926 --> 00:10:23,329
"'Turn her head away from these steaming rapids "'and hug the rock.

97
00:10:23,309 --> 00:10:28,094
or she will give you the slip and be over yonder before you know where you are and you will be the death of us."

98
00:10:29,495 --> 00:10:37,203
So they did as I told them, but I said nothing about the awful monster Scylla, for I knew the men would not go on rowing if I did but would huddle together in the hold.

99
00:10:37,703 --> 00:10:41,287
In one thing only did I disobey Cersei's strict instructions.

100
00:10:41,908 --> 00:10:42,888
I put on my armor.

101
00:10:43,449 --> 00:10:51,477
Then, seizing two strong spears, I took my stand on the ship's bows, for it was there that I expected first to see the monster of the rock.

102
00:10:51,457 --> 00:10:59,694
who was to do my men so much harm, but I could not make her out anywhere, though I strained my eyes with looking the gloomy rock all over and over.

103
00:11:00,476 --> 00:11:08,031
Then we entered the straits in great fear of mind, for on the one hand was Scylla, and on the other Dread Charybdis kept sucking up the salt water.

104
00:11:08,011 --> 00:11:15,623
As she vomited it up, it was like the water in a cauldron when it is boiling over upon a great fire, and the spray reached the top of the rocks on either side.

105
00:11:16,224 --> 00:11:24,057
When she began to suck again, we could see the water all inside whirling round and round, and it made a deafening sound as it broke against the rocks.

106
00:11:24,678 --> 00:11:30,087
We could see the bottom of the whirlpool all black with sand and mud, and the men were at their wits' ends for fear.

107
00:11:30,674 --> 00:11:38,565
While we were taken up with this, and were expecting each moment to be our last, Scylla pounced down suddenly upon us and snatched up my six best men.

108
00:11:39,286 --> 00:11:51,383
I was looking at once after both ship and men, and in a moment I saw their hands and feet ever so high above me, struggling in the air as Scylla was carrying them off, and I heard them call out my name in one last despairing cry.

109
00:11:51,363 --> 00:12:06,975
As a fisherman, seated, spear in hand, upon some jutting rock twenty-four throws bait into the water to deceive the poor little fishes, and spears them with the ox's horn with which his spear is shod, throwing them gasping onto the land as he catches them one by one.

110
00:12:06,955 --> 00:12:15,987
Even so did Scylla land these panting creatures on her rock and munch them up at the mouth of her den, while they screamed and stretched out their hands to me in their mortal agony.

111
00:12:16,587 --> 00:12:19,932
This was the most sickening sight that I saw throughout all my voyages.

112
00:12:20,532 --> 00:12:29,544
When we had passed the wandering rocks with Scylla and terrible Charybdis, we reached the noble island of the Sun God, where were the goodly cattle and sheep belonging to the Sun Hyperion.

113
00:12:30,045 --> 00:12:34,971
While still at sea in my ship, I could bear the cattle lowing as they came home to the yards, and the sheep bleating.

114
00:12:34,951 --> 00:12:44,186
Then I remembered what the blind Theban prophet Teresias had told me, and how carefully Aeon Circe had warned me to shun the island of the blessed sun-god.

115
00:12:44,807 --> 00:13:00,132
So being much troubled I said to the men, My men, I know you are hard-pressed, but listen while I tell you the prophecy that Teresias made me, and how carefully Aeon Circe warned me to shun the island of the blessed sun-god, for it was here, she said, that our worst danger would lie.

116
00:13:00,517 --> 00:13:03,400
Head the ship, therefore, away from the island."

117
00:13:03,420 --> 00:13:07,444
The men were in despair at this, and Eurylochus at once gave me an insolent answer.

118
00:13:07,464 --> 00:13:27,604
"'Ulysses,' said he, "'you are cruel, you are very strong yourself and never get worn out, you seem to be made of iron, and now, though your men are exhausted with toil and want of sleep, you will not let them land and cook themselves a good supper upon this island, but bid them put out to sea and go faring fruitlessly on through the watches of the flying night.'"

119
00:13:27,584 --> 00:13:30,968
It is by night that the winds blow hardest and do so much damage.

120
00:13:31,469 --> 00:13:39,639
How can we escape should one of those sudden squalls spring up from southwest or west, which so often wreck a vessel when our lords, the gods, are unpropitious?

121
00:13:40,239 --> 00:13:45,846
Now, therefore, let us obey the behests of night and prepare our supper here hard by the ship.

122
00:13:46,246 --> 00:13:49,350
Tomorrow morning we will go on board again and put out to sea."

123
00:13:50,291 --> 00:13:53,355
Thus spoke Eurylochus, and the men approved his words.

124
00:13:53,335 --> 00:13:58,923
I saw that heaven meant us a mischief, and said, You force me to yield, for you are many against one.

125
00:13:59,644 --> 00:14:11,681
But at any rate, each one of you must take his solemn oath, that if he meet with a herd of cattle or a large flock of sheep, he will not be so mad as to kill a single head of either, but will be satisfied with the food that Circe has given us.

126
00:14:12,923 --> 00:14:22,296
They all swore as I bade them, and when they had completed their oath we made the ship fast in a harbour that was near a stream of fresh water, and the men went ashore and cooked their suppers.

127
00:14:22,276 --> 00:14:28,545
As soon as they had had enough to eat and drink, they began talking about their poor comrades whom Scylla had snatched up and eaten.

128
00:14:29,005 --> 00:14:33,091
This set them weeping, and they went on crying till they fell off into a sound sleep.

129
00:14:33,812 --> 00:14:46,410
In the third watch of the night when the stars had shifted their places, Jove raised a great gale of wind that flew a hurricane so that land and sea were covered with thick clouds, and night sprang forth out of the heavens.

130
00:14:47,251 --> 00:14:58,442
When the child of morning, rosy-fingered Dawn, appeared, we brought the ship to land, and drew her into a cave wherein the sea-nymphs hold their courts and dances, and I called the men together in council.

131
00:14:58,963 --> 00:15:11,635
My friends, said I, we have meat and drink in the ship, let us mind, therefore, and not touch the cattle, or we shall suffer for it, for these cattle and she belong to the mighty sun, who sees and gives ear to everything.

132
00:15:12,576 --> 00:15:15,199
And again they promised that they would obey.

133
00:15:15,179 --> 00:15:21,529
For a whole month the wind blew steadily from the south, and there was no other wind, but only south and east 105.

134
00:15:22,311 --> 00:15:26,417
As long as corn and wine held out, the men did not touch the cattle when they were hungry.

135
00:15:26,778 --> 00:15:37,255
When, however, they had eaten all there was in the ship, they were forced to go further afield with hook and line, catching birds, and taking whatever they could lay their hands on, for they were starving.

136
00:15:37,235 --> 00:15:42,682
One day, therefore, I went up inland, that I might pray heaven to show me some means of getting away.

137
00:15:42,742 --> 00:15:55,017
When I had gone far enough to be clear of all my men, and had found a place that was well sheltered from the wind, I washed my hands and prayed to all the gods in Olympus till by and by they sent me off into a sweet sleep.

138
00:15:55,517 --> 00:15:58,521
Meanwhile, Eurylochus had been giving evil counsel to the men.

139
00:15:58,941 --> 00:16:05,149
Listen to me, said he, my poor comrades, all deaths are bad enough, but there is none so bad as famine.

140
00:16:05,129 --> 00:16:10,077
Why should not we drive in the best of these cows and offer them in sacrifice to the immortal gods?

141
00:16:10,858 --> 00:16:20,995
If we ever get back to Ithaca, we can build a fine temple to the sun god and enrich it with every kind of ornament, if, however, he is determined to sink our ship out of revenge for these horned cattle.

142
00:16:21,278 --> 00:16:30,740
the other gods are of the same mind, I for one would rather drink salt water once for all and have done with it, than be starved to death by inches in such a desert island as this is."

143
00:16:31,602 --> 00:16:34,388
Thus spoke Eurylochus, and the men approved his words.

144
00:16:34,769 --> 00:16:38,798
Now the cattle, so fair and goodly, were feeding not far from the ship.

145
00:16:38,778 --> 00:16:47,675
The men therefore drove in the best of them, and they all stood round them saying their prayers and using young oak shoots instead of barley meal, for there was no barley left.

146
00:16:48,256 --> 00:16:51,442
When they had done praying, they killed the cows and dressed their carcasses.

147
00:16:51,943 --> 00:16:57,594
They cut out the thigh bones, wrapped them round in two layers of fat, and set some pieces of raw meat on top of them.

148
00:16:58,074 --> 00:17:02,102
They had no wine with which to make drink offerings over the sacrifice while it was cooking,

149
00:17:02,082 --> 00:17:06,570
So they kept pouring on a little water from time to time while the inward meats were being grilled.

150
00:17:06,971 --> 00:17:13,582
Then, when the thigh bones were burned and they had tasted the inward meats, they cut the rest up small and put the pieces upon the spits.

151
00:17:14,163 --> 00:17:19,332
By this time my deep sleep had left me, and I turned back to the ship and to the seashore.

152
00:17:19,312 --> 00:17:25,564
As I drew near, I began to smell hot roast meat, so I groaned out a prayer to the immortal gods.

153
00:17:25,584 --> 00:17:33,779
Father Jove, I exclaimed, and all you other gods who live in everlasting bliss, you have done me a cruel mischief by the sleep into which you have sent me.

154
00:17:34,080 --> 00:17:37,827
See what fine work these men of mine have been making in my absence.

155
00:17:37,807 --> 00:17:58,971
Meanwhile Lampety went straight off to the sun and told him we had been killing his cows, whereon he flew into a great rage and said to the immortals, Father Jove and all you other gods who live in everlasting bliss, I must have vengeance on the crew of Ulysses' ship, they have had the insolence to kill my cows which were the one thing I loved to look upon, whether I was going up heaven or down again.

156
00:17:58,951 --> 00:18:05,122
If they do not square accounts with me about my cows, I will go down to Hades and shine there among the dead.

157
00:18:06,184 --> 00:18:11,073
Son, said Jove, go on shining upon us gods and upon mankind over the fruitful earth.

158
00:18:11,694 --> 00:18:16,183
I will shiver their ship into little pieces with a bolt of white lightning as soon as they get out to sea.

159
00:18:16,904 --> 00:18:21,212
I was told all this by Calypso, who said she had heard it from the mouth of Mercury.

160
00:18:21,192 --> 00:18:29,221
As soon as I got down to my ship and to the seashore I rebuked each one of the men separately, but we could see no way out of it, for the cows were dead already.

161
00:18:29,902 --> 00:18:43,297
And indeed the gods began at once to show signs and wonders among us, for the hides of the cattle crawled about, and the joints upon the spits began to low like cows, and the meat, whether cooked or raw, kept on making a noise just as cows do.

162
00:18:43,897 --> 00:18:48,162
For six days my men kept driving in the best cows and feasting upon them,

163
00:18:48,142 --> 00:18:52,828
But when Jove the son of Saturn had added a seventh day, the fury of the gale abated.

164
00:18:53,249 --> 00:18:57,414
We therefore went on board, raised our masts, spread sail, and put out to sea.

165
00:18:57,975 --> 00:19:07,247
As soon as we were well away from the island, and could see nothing but sky and sea, the son of Saturn raised a black cloud over our ship, and the sea grew dark beneath it.

166
00:19:07,227 --> 00:19:17,977
We did not get on much further, for in another moment we were caught by a terrific squall from the west that snapped the forestays of the mast so that it fell aft, while all the ship's gear tumbled about at the bottom of the vessel.

167
00:19:18,677 --> 00:19:27,846
The mast fell upon the head of the helmsman in the ship's stern, so that the bones of his head were crushed to pieces, and he fell overboard as though he were diving, with no more life left in him.

168
00:19:28,426 --> 00:19:35,833
Then Jove let fly with his thunderbolts, and the ship went round and round, and was filled with fire and brimstone as the lightning struck it.

169
00:19:35,813 --> 00:19:37,239
The men all fell into the sea.

170
00:19:37,841 --> 00:19:41,556
They were carried about in the water round the ship, looking like so many seagulls.

171
00:19:42,239 --> 00:19:45,452
But the god presently deprived them of all chance of getting home again.

172
00:19:46,006 --> 00:20:02,806
I stuck to the ship till the sea knocked her sides from her keel, which drifted about by itself, and struck the mast out of her in the direction of the keel, but there was a backstay of stout ox thongs still hanging about it, and with this I lashed the mast and keel together, and getting astride of them was carried wherever the winds chose to take me.

173
00:20:03,587 --> 00:20:12,638
The gale from the west had now spent its force, and the wind got into the south again, which frightened me lest I should be taken back to the terrible whirlpool of Charybdis.

174
00:20:13,124 --> 00:20:21,615
This indeed was what actually happened, for I was borne along by the waves all night, and by sunrise had reached the rock of Scylla and the whirlpool.

175
00:20:22,196 --> 00:20:30,386
She was then sucking down the salt seawater weather 106, but I was carried aloft toward the fig tree, which I caught hold of and clung on to like a bat.

176
00:20:30,927 --> 00:20:42,962
I could not plant my feet anywhere so as to stand securely, for the roots were a long way off, and the boughs that overshadowed the whole pool were too high, too vast, and too far apart for me to reach them, so I hung patiently on.

177
00:20:42,942 --> 00:20:47,749
waiting till the pool should discharge my mast and raft again, and a very long while it seemed.

178
00:20:48,410 --> 00:20:58,384
A jury man is not more glad to get home to supper, after having been long detained in court by troublesome cases, than I was to see my raft beginning to work its way out of the whirlpool again.

179
00:20:58,424 --> 00:21:07,617
At last I let go with my hands and feet, and fell heavily into the sea, hard by my raft on to which I then got, and began to row with my hands.

180
00:21:07,597 --> 00:21:13,754
As for Scylla, the father of gods and men would not let her get further sight of me, otherwise I should have certainly been lost.

181
00:21:14,055 --> 00:21:14,596
